[
    {
        "content": "<p>I put forward my question in <a href=\"https://rust-lang.zulipchat.com/#narrow/channel/425075-rust-for-linux/topic/Review.20about.20the.20safety.20comment.20related.20to.20List.3A.3Aremove/with/567645786\">https://rust-lang.zulipchat.com/#narrow/channel/425075-rust-for-linux/topic/Review.20about.20the.20safety.20comment.20related.20to.20List.3A.3Aremove/with/567645786</a>,  and maybe it's better to post my question in Rust-for-linux zulip, so I copy my question as follows,  but the above link already has some discussion.</p>\n<p>Several weeks ago, the Rust code in the Linux Kernel saw its <strong><a href=\"https://www.phoronix.com/news/First-Linux-Rust-CVE\">first CVE vulnerability</a></strong>. After reading the patch for this CVE, I think the safety comment for <strong><a href=\"https://www.kernel.org/doc/rustdoc/next/kernel/list/struct.List.html#method.remove\">List::remove</a></strong> could be modified to prevent potential misuse.</p>\n<p>A post on <strong><a href=\"https://www.reddit.com/r/rust/comments/1pp3y9e/comment/nulcc6r/?utm_source=share&amp;utm_medium=web3x&amp;utm_name=web3xcss&amp;utm_term=1&amp;utm_content=share_button\">Reddit</a></strong> introduces the related code for this CVE. This CVE involved a possible data race condition when traversing and simultaneously removing elements from the same list. The main reason is that the buggy function drops the list's lock while the list is being traversed:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Rust\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"k\">impl</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Node</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"c1\">// [Other bits omitted]</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">pub</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"k\">crate</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">fn</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">release</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"o\">&amp;</span><span class=\"bp\">self</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"kd\">let</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">mut</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">guard</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">self</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">owner</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">inner</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">lock</span><span class=\"p\">();</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"c1\">// [omitted]</span>\n\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"kd\">let</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">death_list</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">core</span><span class=\"p\">::</span><span class=\"n\">mem</span><span class=\"p\">::</span><span class=\"n\">take</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"o\">&amp;</span><span class=\"k\">mut</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">self</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">inner</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">access_mut</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"o\">&amp;</span><span class=\"k\">mut</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">guard</span><span class=\"p\">).</span><span class=\"n\">death_list</span><span class=\"p\">);</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"nb\">drop</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">guard</span><span class=\"p\">);</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"k\">for</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">death</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">in</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">death_list</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">            </span><span class=\"n\">death</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">into_arc</span><span class=\"p\">().</span><span class=\"n\">set_dead</span><span class=\"p\">();</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"p\">}</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"p\">}</span>\n<span class=\"p\">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>Thus, the removal and traversal operations can happen simultaneously.</p>\n<p>The CVE patch fixes the data race by acquiring the lock before every pop operation:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Rust\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"k\">pub</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"k\">crate</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">fn</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">release</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"o\">&amp;</span><span class=\"bp\">self</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"kd\">let</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">mut</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">guard</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">self</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">owner</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">inner</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">lock</span><span class=\"p\">();</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"c1\">// [Other bits omitted]</span>\n\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">while</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kd\">let</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nb\">Some</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">death</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">self</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">inner</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">access_mut</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"o\">&amp;</span><span class=\"k\">mut</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">guard</span><span class=\"p\">).</span><span class=\"n\">death_list</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">pop_front</span><span class=\"p\">()</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"nb\">drop</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"n\">guard</span><span class=\"p\">);</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"n\">death</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">into_arc</span><span class=\"p\">().</span><span class=\"n\">set_dead</span><span class=\"p\">();</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"n\">guard</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">self</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">owner</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">inner</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">lock</span><span class=\"p\">();</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"p\">}</span>\n<span class=\"p\">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>However, the <code>remove</code> operation itself satisfied its safety comment, and the maintainer provided the <code>#SAFETY</code> comment at the call site:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Rust\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"c1\">// The source code of List::remove</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"sd\">/// Removes the provided item from this list and returns it.</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"sd\">///</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"sd\">/// This returns `None` if the item is not in the list. (Note that by the safety requirements,</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"sd\">/// this means that the item is not in any list.)</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"sd\">///</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"sd\">/// When using this method, be careful with using `mem::take` on the same list as that may</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"sd\">/// result in violating the safety requirements of this method.</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"sd\">///</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"sd\">/// # Safety</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"sd\">///</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"sd\">/// `item` must not be in a different linked list (with the same id).</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">pub</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">unsafe</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">fn</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">remove</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"o\">&amp;</span><span class=\"k\">mut</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">self</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">item</span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kp\">&amp;</span><span class=\"nc\">T</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nb\">Option</span><span class=\"o\">&lt;</span><span class=\"n\">ListArc</span><span class=\"o\">&lt;</span><span class=\"n\">T</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ID</span><span class=\"o\">&gt;&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"c1\">// omit the implementation</span>\n<span class=\"p\">}</span>\n\n<span class=\"c1\">// The call site of List::remove</span>\n<span class=\"k\">impl</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">NodeDeath</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"c1\">// [Other bits omitted]</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"sd\">/// Sets the cleared flag to `true`.</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"sd\">///</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"sd\">/// It removes `self` from the node's death notification list if needed.</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"sd\">///</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"sd\">/// Returns whether it needs to be queued.</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"k\">pub</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"k\">crate</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">fn</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">set_cleared</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"bp\">self</span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kp\">&amp;</span><span class=\"nc\">DArc</span><span class=\"o\">&lt;</span><span class=\"bp\">Self</span><span class=\"o\">&gt;</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">abort</span><span class=\"p\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">bool</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">-&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">bool</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"c1\">// [Removed some hopefully-not-relevant code]</span>\n\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"c1\">// Remove death notification from node.</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"k\">if</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">needs_removal</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span>\n<span class=\"w\">            </span><span class=\"kd\">let</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">mut</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">owner_inner</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">self</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">node</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">owner</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">inner</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">lock</span><span class=\"p\">();</span>\n<span class=\"w\">            </span><span class=\"kd\">let</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">node_inner</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">self</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">node</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">inner</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">access_mut</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"o\">&amp;</span><span class=\"k\">mut</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">owner_inner</span><span class=\"p\">);</span>\n<span class=\"w\">            </span><span class=\"c1\">// SAFETY: A `NodeDeath` is never inserted into the death list of any node other than</span>\n<span class=\"w\">            </span><span class=\"c1\">// its owner, so it is either in this death list or in no death list.</span>\n<span class=\"w\">            </span><span class=\"k\">unsafe</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">node_inner</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">death_list</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"n\">remove</span><span class=\"p\">(</span><span class=\"bp\">self</span><span class=\"p\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">};</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"p\">}</span>\n<span class=\"w\">        </span><span class=\"n\">needs_queueing</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"p\">}</span>\n<span class=\"p\">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>Currently, the safety comment for <code>List::remove</code> reminds users to be careful with using <code>mem::take</code>, but it seems the main reason for this CVE was that the lack of a lock caused the traversal and removal operations to happen simultaneously.</p>\n<p>So I have the following questions:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>\n<p>Why might <code>mem::take</code> result in violating the safety requirements of <code>List::remove</code>? It seems that <code>mem::take</code> simply takes the list from <code>Self</code> and stores it on the stack, and the item intended for removal is in the same list. </p>\n</li>\n<li>\n<p>I propose adding a safety requirement entry for <code>List::remove</code>: <strong>When performing the removal operation, the caller must hold the lock for this list.</strong> This will guarantee that no data race can occur.</p>\n</li>\n</ol>",
